<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by GL Assessment</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 4.75pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OAR0003</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 4.75pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GL Assessment </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 11.15pt; padding-left:12.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.83pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a division of the GL Education Group, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a leading provider of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> independent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tests and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> assessments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including stakeholder surveys.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL Assessment specialises in literacy, numeracy, reasoning, SEN and attitudinal assessments, and has relationships with over 85% of UK primary and secondary schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Taking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a scientific, rigorous approach to identify ability, guide improvement and deliver results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e focus on working closely with educators to provide real insights that help </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> make a genuine improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.35pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Ofsted Annual Report specifically highlights low level poor behaviour in classrooms and poor attainment amongst white, disadvantaged children as areas of concern. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that the best means of improvin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g the attainment of all pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is through the use of consistent formative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and attitudinal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> assessments and intervention programmes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.27pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Formative assessments allow schools to identify pupil’s learning difficulties, while attitudinal assessments can pinpoint the causes of any behavioural problems. Tackling these together will improve attainment, help address the underachievement of white, disadvantaged children and tackle poor behaviour in the classroom. In addition, formative assessments provide an efficient and accurate means of measuring the effective use of Pupil Premium funding. We believe that schools should be placing a greater emphasis on using this additional funding to build consistent and comprehensive programmes of formative assessment.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.75pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Ofsted Annual Report 2012/14 highlights low level poor behaviour in classrooms as a major challenge in schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It states that in “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a minority of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools…</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leadersh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ip loses focus on the essential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">job of ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high standards of behaviour and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improving teaching and learning. In these schoo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ls, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">low-level misbehavio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ur in the classroom often slows </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pupils’ progress.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.27pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Formative assessments play an important role in tackling this poor behaviour. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is important that schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> apply a rigorous and scientific approach to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a full understanding of the attitudes of pupils towards education. Negative attitudes to school can lead to poor behaviour. It is therefore important that schools assess pupil attitudes and work to address any problems. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.79pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pupil Attitudes to Self and School</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PASS) attitudinal survey is used </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by over 2500 schools and over 100 local authorities across the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to address behavioural problems. The survey is comprised of short psychometric statements that feed into nine attitudinal factors linked to key educational goals. These include how well children are responding to the curriculum, how prepared they are to learn and their attitude towards attendance. A low score in any factor can accurately pinpoint negative attitudes that may not otherwise be apparent. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.32pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disengagement, poor attitudes to attendance and low self-confidence can manifest as poor behaviour and ultimately have serious detrimental impacts on pupil attainment. PASS can help to identify previously unknown areas where pupils may be disengaged or having difficulties and help schools to introduce targeted interventions before these problems become entrenched. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#4c4d4f; font-family:undryFormSans-Book; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.28pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The introduction of the Pupil Premium has been a valuable way of providing targeted support to</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disadvantaged</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pupils</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, who are often those with the most difficult behavioural issues</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The Annual Report notes that “Stronger schools are much more likely to evaluate fully the impact that </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the pupil premium</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> investment is having</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on disadvantaged pupils.</span><span style="color:#4c4d4f; font-family:undryFormSans-Book; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that this funding should be used by schools to support the </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation of formative assessment and intervention regimes, including those which identify behavioural issues. The Government should therefore be encouraging schools to use the Pupil Premium to provide extra funding for formative assessments to demonstrate the impact of the interventions they have put in place. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#4c4d4f; font-family:undryFormSans-Book; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#4c4d4f; font-family:undryFormSans-Book; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pupil Premium funding would also be wisely spent by schools on identifying </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas where </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">white, disadvantaged</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pupils need extra support</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. By consistently monitoring their progress, any attainment gap can be narrowed before the time they reach summative examinations. Indeed, the underperformance of white, disadvantaged children is an area that the</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Ofsted Annual Report </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> highlights as a major challenge facing England’s education system. It states that </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the long tail</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of underperformance of</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> White children from low income </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">backgrounds i</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s limiting our progress towards </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a world class educat</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion system. Compared with other </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnic groups of pupils </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from low income families, white </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children have the lowest attainment.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.07pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that the best means of improving the attainment of all pupils, including white, disadvantaged children, is through the use of consistent formative assessments and intervention programmes. Using these assessments, schools can identify those pupils that are underachieving, understand the causes of these problems and introduce targeted interventions to tackle them. These assessments also provide an accurate means of assessing if those interventions have successfully narrowed the attainment gap and by implication, if Pupil Premium funding has been spent effectively.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important that the assessments used as part of such a regime provide detailed, standardised reporting specifically on the results achieved by white working class children. This allows a direct comparison to be made between these children and their more advantaged peers, both in their school and nationally. For example, one assessment that is widely used in UK schools, particularly at the transition between primary and secondary school, is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cognitive Abilities Test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (CAT). CAT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cannot be prepared for as it measures underlying reasoning abilities and therefore provides schools with a comprehensive profile of a pupil’s developed abilities.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It enables schools to identify pupils’ potential, set </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aspirational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> targets and drive school improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.11pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CAT provides schools with a solid basis for introducing targeted interventions to improve pupil attainment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> literacy and numeracy. Ideally it is used in conjunction with other formative assessments such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Progress in Maths</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PiM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Progress in English</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PiE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) which assess attainment as well as ability levels in maths and English. By comparing these results to CAT scores, teachers can see where pupils are not yet reaching their potential and implement improvement strategies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as providing detailed reporting on individual pupils, which is key for the identification of those pupils in need of targeted support, CAT also provides analysis of the results of pupils by group, including by gender and ethnicity and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those eligible for free school meals. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.03pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As CAT is a nationally standardised test, schools can compare the results of these groups of pupils to other pupils in their cohort, not only within the school but also at a national level. Comparisons by gender or ethnicity can help schools identify if there are any particular areas of difficulty among white children compared to children of other ethnicities, and introduce appropriate support to tackle these issues. Schools should be encouraged to collect this type of data by governing bodies and local authorities. This will help them to understand how working class pupils at the schools they are responsible for are achieving and identify what work needs to be undertaken to improve the outcomes of these pupils. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.51pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By using comprehensive and consistent programmes of formative assessment, such as CAT, to track pupil progress, identify pupil difficulties and pinpoint the causes of any behavioural problems, schools will be in a much stronger position to tackle two of the areas of concern highlighted by Ofsted in its Annual Report 2012/13.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Ofsted Annual Report 2012-13, Schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, pg 25</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Ofsted Annual Report 2012-13, Schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, pg 24</span></p></body></html>